: Genealogies and Global Contexts, 1860–1957 -- t11. The Science of Sexual Difference: Ogura Seizaburō, Hiratsuka Raichō, and the Intersection of Sexology and Feminism in Early-Twentieth-Century Japan -- t12. Time for Sex: Th e Education of Desire and the Conduct of Childhood in Global/Hindu Sexology -- tPART THREE. MOBILITY, TRAVEL, EXILE, AND THE CIRCUITS OF SEXOLOGICAL KNOWLEDGE -- t13. Latin Eugenics and Sexual Knowledge in Italy, Spain, and Argentina: International Networks across the Atlantic -- t14. “Forms So Attenuated That They Merge into Normality Itself”: Alexander Lipschütz, Gregorio Marañón, and Theories of Intersexuality in Chile, circa 1930 -- t15. “Tyranny of Orgasm”: Global Governance of Sexuality from Bombay, 1930s–1950s -- t16. Magnus Hirschfeld’s Onnagata -- t17. Agnes Smedley between Berlin, Bombay, and Beijing: Sexology, Communism, and National Independence -- t18. The Limits of Transnationalism: The Case of Max Marcuse -- tAfterword: In the Shadow of Empire: The Words and Worlds of Sexual Science -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStarting in the late nineteenth century, scholars and activists all over the world suddenly began to insist that understandings of sex be based on science. As Japanese and Indian sexologists influenced their German, British, and American counterparts and vice versa, sexuality, modernity, and imaginings of exotified “Others” became intimately linked. The first anthology to provide a worldwide perspective on the birth and development of the field, A Global History of Sexual Science contends that actors outside of Europe—in Asia, Latin America, and Africa—became important interlocutors in debates on prostitution, birth control, and transvestism. Ideas circulated through intellectual exchange, travel, and internationally produced and disseminated publications. Twenty scholars tackle specific issues, including the female orgasm and the criminalization of male homosexuality, to demonstrate how concepts and ideas introduced by sexual scientists gained currency throughout the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSexologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSexologyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  a19th century.  aactivist.  aafrica.  aanthology.  aasia.  abiology.  abirth control.  abirth.  acontemporary.  acrime.  acriminalization.  adevelopment.  aeurope.  aeuropean.  afemale orgasm.  aglobal.  ahuman sexuality.  ainternational.  alatin america.  alegal issues.  amale homosexuality.  amodern world.  aother.  aothers.  aprostitution.  ascholar.  ascholars.  ascience.  asex.  asexologist.  asexual science.  asexual scientists.  asexuality.  atransvestism.  atravel.1 aAhluwalia, Sanjam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeccalossi, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBotre, Shrikant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiang, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuechtner, Veronika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuechtner, Veronika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFunke, Jana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaynes, Douglas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaynes, Douglas E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerrn, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc